Automotive Auctioneering Antics: Predicting Price with Dealer-Provided Datapoints

Marina Cui, Oliver Yun, Sam You

2021-12-09

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = FALSE, message = FALSE, warning = FALSE)

Introduction

The dataset US Cars Dataset is excerpted from Kaggle, as published by Kaggle user Doaa Alsenani. The data was scraped from Auction Export.com by the aforementioned Kaggle user in April 2020. This dataset contains data on cars listed on Auction Export.com, a car auctioning website, up to year 2020. Each case is an auctioned car, and the variables pertain to information on the car condition and price. The dataset contains 2499 observations of 13 variables, which are listed below in the codebook. -Dataset -Previous Work -Research Questions

Analysis

Variables

Sorting through the variables after establishing price as the response variable, the remaining continuous explanatory variables are mileage normalised through a square-root transformation, lot, vehicle age in years (years_old), and hours left in auction (hours_left).

In order, it is expected, on average; people are less willing to buy more heavily used vehicles, such that an increase in mileage should negatively correlate; lot has no correlation with price; people are less willing to buy older vehicles, such that an increase in how many years old a vehicle is will negatively correlate; and people will rush to put bids on auctions about to close, thus hours left should negatively correlate.

The above correlation plot indicates that mileage and vehicle age correlate most strongly with price, while having a negative correlation with each other. Lot number has a minor positive correlation with price, indicating the likely presence of noise. Hours left in the auction has no correlation with price, mileage, or vehicle age, perhaps indicating that bidding generally occurs relatively early in the auction process - it is, in any case, irrelevant to the question of price.

This leaves the following categorical variables; brand, model, title status, color, and state.

Model 2

Price versus title status

In this section, we would like to learn about how cars with difference title status differ in their price.

Relationsip exploration

Make a side-by-side box plot displaying the relationship between title_status and price of the vehicles listed on Auction Export.com.

Calculate the mean and median price for cars in clean vehicle status and cars in salvage insurance status.

## # A tibble: 1  2
##   mean_price median_price
##        <dbl>        <dbl>
## 1       135.         134.
## # A tibble: 1  2
##   mean_price median_price
##        <dbl>        <dbl>
## 1       33.9         28.7

Bootstrap calculation

Use bootstrap to quantify the uncertainty in the sample estimates. Also, visualize the bootstrap distribution and calculate a 95% confidence interval. 

## # A tibble: 1  2
##   lower_ci upper_ci
##      <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1     95.4     106.

Conclusion

According to the box plots above, the middle 50% of price(sqrt) for cars with clean vehicle status is much higher than that of cars with salvage insurance status; also, according to the calculated summaries, both the mean and median of price(sqrt) for cars with clean vehicle status (mean: 135, median: 134) are more than that of cars with salvage insurance status (mean: 45.2, median: 42.6). In other words, cars with clean vehicle status usually has much higher price than cars with salvage insurance status.

We are 95% confident that the average price difference in this car auction website between the cars with different title status is greater than 7022.44 and smaller than 9158.49 dollars.

Year versus condition

In this section, we would like to examine the relationship between year and condition on whether or not these two variables are independent. The null hypothesis is that year and condition are independent.

Recoding values

We need to recode hours_left as a new variable converted_c, which takes the value more than a day when hours_left > 24 and less than a day when hours_left <= 24. Also N/A values are remain as N/As in the new column.

We also need to recode year as a new variable before_2019 which takes the value yes when year < 2019 and no when year >= 2019.

Relationship exploration

Make a segmented bar chart visualizing the relationship between before_2019 and converted_c.

Find count for each group and calculate the observed difference in proportions between before and after 2019 that is on the auction website for less than a day.

## # A tibble: 4  4
## # Groups:   before_2019 [2]
##   before_2019 converted_c         n  prop
##   <chr>       <chr>           <int> <dbl>
## 1 no          less than a day   362 0.387
## 2 no          more than a day   574 0.613
## 3 yes         less than a day   713 0.462
## 4 yes         more than a day   830 0.538

Hypothesis testing

Create and visualize null distribution. Also, get the p-value to quantify the evidence against the null hypothesis of independence.

## # A tibble: 1  1
##   p_value
##     <dbl>
## 1  0.0016

Conclusion

A p-value of 0.0012 tells us that our data doesnt fit the null hypothesis very well. In other words, year and condition are dependent.

In terms of 1% level of significance, p-value of 0.0012 is smaller than that, thus by accepting the alternative hypothesis, we have enough evidence to say that year and condition are dependent.
